{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Renée C. Kraan-Korteweg | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1954|05|07}} | birth_place = [[Amsterdam]] | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | pronounce = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Basle]], Switzerland | thesis_title = <!--(or | thesis1_title = and | thesis2_title = )--> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = <!--(or | thesis1_year = and | thesis2_year = )--> | doctoral_advisor = Prof. Dr. G.A. Tammann | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = Pieter Kraan | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }}
Professor '''Renée C. Kraan-Korteweg''' (born 1954) is a Dutch - South African scientist.
She is Head of the Department of Astronomy at the [[University of Cape Town]] as well as Founder and Co-director of the Astrophysics, Cosmology and Gravity Centre.<ref>http://www.ast.uct.ac.za/~kraan/cv.html</ref> She also serves as Vice-President of Executive Committee of the [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref>https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/6929/</ref> She is a member of the [[Academy of Science of South Africa]].<ref>https://www.assaf.org.za/index.php/about-assaf/members#S</ref>
Her research interests include the [[Large-scale structure of the Cosmos|Large Scale Structure]] and streaming motions in the nearby universe. She also conducts research with the South African Large Telescope (SALT), including searching for [[Black hole|black holes]] in the centre of [[dwarf elliptical galaxies]] and looking at how much [[dark matter]] there is in low surface brightness galaxies<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mensa.ast.uct.ac.za/~kraan/|title=Personal|website=mensa.ast.uct.ac.za|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref>. She was one of the lead authors in the breakthrough paper “The Parkes HI Zone of Avoidance Survey”<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Staveley-Smith|first=L.|last2=Kraan-Korteweg|first2=R. C.|last3=Schröder|first3=A. C.|last4=Henning|first4=P. A.|last5=Koribalski|first5=B. S.|last6=Stewart|first6=I. M.|last7=Heald|first7=G.|date=2016|title=The Parkes H I Zone of Avoidance Survey|url=http://stacks.iop.org/1538-3881/151/i=3/a=52|journal=The Astronomical Journal|language=en|volume=151|issue=3|pages=52|doi=10.3847/0004-6256/151/3/52|issn=1538-3881|arxiv=1602.02922}}</ref>, which used the Parkes 60m Radio Telescope to discover nearby galaxies that were previously "hidden" by the gravitational anomaly known as the [[Great Attractor]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.saao.ac.za/press-release/sa-astronomers-help-discover-hidden-galaxies-behind-milky-way/|title=SA astronomers help discover hidden galaxies behind Milky Way|date=2016-02-10|work=SAAO|access-date=2018-07-26|language=en-US}}</ref>.
